	<entry>
		<title type="html">Compiz: Shadows Plugin</title>
		<link href="http://ogunderground.com/article.php?id=29"/>
		<id>http://ogunderground.com/article.php?id=29</id>
		<updated>2008-06-03T20:18:17+00:00</updated>
		<content type="html">Right, so a few weeks ago I started working on a shadow plugin that will, when complete, render better shadows for windows based on their actual physical stacking order. Now, I haven't gotten anything done recently (and I can't seem to push to my git repo...), but I'd like to give a basic overview of what *is* done and what has yet to be started:&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;First off, all that works is a simple little loop that gathers depth information. If you clone my repo and uncomment a block of code (it should be pretty obvious which block), the plugin will physically stack windows three-dimensionally (it's just the code I wrote for Wiitrack, minus the tracking and projection changing). That's all it does right now, so don't bother doing anything with it.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Now, of course, it's far from done, but let's look at what it will do:&lt;br /&gt;1. First we grab the depth information, as above.&lt;br /&gt;2. Second, when painting the current window, we'll loop through the windows above this one.&lt;br /&gt;3. We'll take each of those individual windows' alpha maps and blur them some how. Tons of possibilities here. We'll also change the opacity level of the new shadow maps and displace them a bit based on their height from this window.&lt;br /&gt;4. Next step is to merge these blurred and displaced textures into one shadow map.&lt;br /&gt;5. And finally, it gets drawn on top of the window.&lt;br /&gt;6. Next window!&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;http://ogunderground.com/article.php?id=29&quot;&gt;Discuss this news post here&lt;/a&gt;.</content>
